                                                                                           Q7.Business questions
                                                                                Does low product usage increase churn risk?
                                                         Query
SELECT
	CASE
	WHEN product_usage = 0.00 THEN 'low_use'
	ELSE 'high_use'
	END AS product_cat,
	COUNT(*)total_users,
	SUM(CASE WHEN churned = 'Churned' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)Churned_users,
	ROUND(
	SUM(CASE WHEN churned = 'Churned' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) *100/COUNT(*)
	)churn_rate
FROM user_monthly
GROUP BY product_cat;


                                                            Finding:
The total number of users that did not use the product are higher than those that used it. Also, those that used the product had higher churn rate compared to those that did not use 

                                                       Why did it happen?
Further analysis showed that many users who churned logged in infrequently, but when they did, they used the product effectively. Also, they submitted more support tickets and reported lower satisfaction scores,
suggesting that low engagement and unresolved issues contributed to churn.

                                                     Why should leadership care?
Losing these users may result in a decrease in sales and profitability and acquisition of new customers can be costly

                                                              Recommendation?
Introduce proactive customer support for users with declining login frequency, simplify key product workflows, and encourage consistent engagement through personalized in-app guidance.






